### Collision as Impulse Force

A ball hits the ground—velocity reverses instantly (infinite force over zero time, modeled as instantaneous velocity change).

```scheme
(define (update t)
  (letrec
    ((step (lambda (y vy frame)
             (if (> frame 500)
                 '()
                 (let* ((gravity 0.5)
                        (ground 380)
                        (restitution 0.75)
                        (new-vy (if (and (>= y ground) (> vy 0))
                                    (* (- restitution) vy)
                                    (+ vy gravity)))
                        (new-y (if (> y ground) ground y)))
                   (cons
                     (draw-circle 200 new-y 12 \"red\")
                     (step (+ new-y new-vy) new-vy (+ frame 1))))))))
    (step 50 0 0)))

(motion 0 500 update)
```

[VISUAL: A red circle bouncing—each bounce lower than the last, energy lost.]

When `y >= ground` and moving down, reverse velocity scaled by `restitution`. Gravity between bounces.

