### Friction on Surface Contact

A sliding object on the ground—friction opposes motion only when touching.

```scheme
(define (update t)
  (letrec
    ((step (lambda (x y vx vy frame)
             (if (> frame 450)
                 '()
                 (let* ((gravity 0.5)
                        (ground 350)
                        (on-ground? (>= y ground))
                        (friction (if on-ground? (* -0.06 vx) 0))
                        (bounce-vy (if (and (>= y ground) (> vy 0)) (* -0.4 vy) vy))
                        (new-vy (if on-ground? 0 (+ bounce-vy gravity)))
                        (new-y (if (> y ground) ground y)))
                   (cons
                     (draw-circle x new-y 11 \"orange\")
                     (step (+ x vx) (+ new-y new-vy)
                           (+ vx friction) new-vy
                           (+ frame 1))))))))
    (step 50 200 3.0 0 0)))

(motion 0 450 update)
```

[VISUAL: An orange circle falling, hitting ground, bouncing weakly, then sliding to a stop—horizontal friction active only when grounded.]

Friction applied only when `on-ground?`. Vertical velocity zeroed on ground (inelastic in vertical). Horizontal velocity decays.

