### Inverse-Square Gravity

Gravitational force proportional to `1 / dist^2`—realistic planetary attraction.

```scheme
(define (update t)
  (letrec
    ((step (lambda (x y vx vy frame)
             (if (> frame 500)
                 '()
                 (let* ((cx 200)
                        (cy 200)
                        (dx (- cx x))
                        (dy (- cy y))
                        (dist-sq (+ (* dx dx) (* dy dy)))
                        (dist (sqrt dist-sq))
                        (strength 500)
                        (force (/ strength dist-sq))
                        (ax (* force (/ dx dist)))
                        (ay (* force (/ dy dist))))
                   (cons
                     (draw-circle x y 7 \"white\")
                     (step (+ x vx) (+ y vy)
                           (+ vx ax) (+ vy ay)
                           (+ frame 1))))))))
    (step 100 200 0 1.2 0)))

(motion 0 500 update)
```

[VISUAL: A white circle orbiting—tighter near the center, looser farther out—elliptical orbit under inverse-square law.]

Force stronger when close. Orbit speed varies—faster near periapsis.

