### Three-Body Problem: Chaotic Motion

Two fixed masses, one object responding to both—unpredictable trajectory.

```scheme
(define (update t)
  (letrec
    ((step (lambda (x y vx vy frame)
             (if (> frame 600)
                 '()
                 (let* ((m1x 120) (m1y 200)
                        (m2x 280) (m2y 200)
                        (dx1 (- m1x x)) (dy1 (- m1y y))
                        (dx2 (- m2x x)) (dy2 (- m2y y))
                        (dist1 (sqrt (+ (* dx1 dx1) (* dy1 dy1))))
                        (dist2 (sqrt (+ (* dx2 dx2) (* dy2 dy2))))
                        (strength 0.5)
                        (ax1 (* strength (/ dx1 dist1)))
                        (ay1 (* strength (/ dy1 dist1)))
                        (ax2 (* strength (/ dx2 dist2)))
                        (ay2 (* strength (/ dy2 dist2)))
                        (total-ax (+ ax1 ax2))
                        (total-ay (+ ay1 ay2)))
                   (cons
                     (draw-circle x y 5 \"green\")
                     (step (+ x vx) (+ y vy)
                           (+ vx total-ax) (+ vy total-ay)
                           (+ frame 1))))))))
    (step 200 100 0.8 0 0)))

(motion 0 600 update)
```

[VISUAL: A green circle weaving between two fixed points—erratic, looping path, sensitive to initial conditions.]

Two attractors pull simultaneously. The resulting motion is chaotic—small changes in start conditions yield wildly different paths.

