### Tidal Force: Differential Gravity

An extended object experiences stronger pull on the near side—stretching force.

*[needs: multi-point rigid body with per-vertex force accumulation]*

<!-- BUILD: entity with multiple attachment points, each feeling independent force, connected by constraints -->

```scheme
(define (update t)
  (letrec
    ((step (lambda (y1 vy1 y2 vy2 frame)
             (if (> frame 400)
                 '()
                 (let* ((planet-y 350)
                        (dy1 (- planet-y y1))
                        (dy2 (- planet-y y2))
                        (dist1 (abs dy1))
                        (dist2 (abs dy2))
                        (strength 0.8)
                        (force1 (/ strength dist1))
                        (force2 (/ strength dist2))
                        (ay1 (* force1 (if (> dy1 0) 1 -1)))
                        (ay2 (* force2 (if (> dy2 0) 1 -1))))
                   (list
                     (draw-circle 200 y1 8 \"red\")
                     (draw-circle 200 y2 8 \"blue\")
                     (step (+ y1 vy1) (+ vy1 ay1)
                           (+ y2 vy2) (+ vy2 ay2)
                           (+ frame 1))))))))
    (step 100 0 150 0 0)))

(motion 0 400 update)
```

[VISUAL: Two circles (ends of a rigid rod) falling toward a planet—lower circle accelerates faster, gap widens—tidal stretching.]

Red closer to planet, feels stronger force. Blue farther, weaker force. Differential acceleration stretches the object.

